1
00:01:02,854 --> 00:01:05,857
Come on! Put it to the floor!

2
00:01:05,982 --> 00:01:08,693
Come on! Let's go!

3
00:01:11,696 --> 00:01:15,617
Go, go, go, go.

4
00:01:23,041 --> 00:01:25,085
Here we go.

5
00:01:25,210 --> 00:01:29,339
Pull over. Pull over!

6
00:01:37,972 --> 00:01:40,350
Slow down, slow down.

7
00:01:55,824 --> 00:01:57,867
Open up!

8
00:02:01,871 --> 00:02:05,625
Defender of the nation,
I bid thee a fond farewell.

9
00:02:06,626 --> 00:02:09,713
Make a million.
Make a million, buddy.

10
00:02:54,758 --> 00:02:59,554
Mike. Lookee there. Look at that.

11
00:02:59,637 --> 00:03:02,640
Look at that.
You see that city out there, kid?

12
00:03:02,766 --> 00:03:06,936
See that big town? One day, we're
gonna own that town, you and me.

13
00:03:07,020 --> 00:03:09,481
What do you think of that?

14
00:03:10,940 --> 00:03:12,400
Smart kid.

15
00:04:27,934 --> 00:04:31,855
Uncle Pat. Be careful
or you'll throw that back out again.

16
00:04:31,980 --> 00:04:36,526
Don't worry. I can handle it.
So, home from the wars?

17
00:04:38,278 --> 00:04:39,279
How are you?

18
00:04:39,404 --> 00:04:43,324
Fine. Servicing all the widows
in the neighbourhood.

19
00:04:43,491 --> 00:04:44,951
Same old Uncle Pat.

20
00:04:46,453 --> 00:04:51,416
Flat beer from rusty pipes.
If you only knew how I missed it.

21
00:04:51,750 --> 00:04:55,003
You've changed, but they
didn't beat the wise guy out of you.

22
00:04:55,086 --> 00:04:58,006
- No chance of that.
- I saved the apartment for you.

23
00:04:58,131 --> 00:05:01,384
Sublet it to two yuppies
who loved your mother's furniture.

24
00:05:01,509 --> 00:05:03,636
They said it was quaint.

25
00:05:03,762 --> 00:05:06,222
I remember the day
they came to repossess it.

26
00:05:06,348 --> 00:05:09,225
Yeah, well.
So, what are you gonna do now?

27
00:05:12,395 --> 00:05:14,022
Make a million.

28
00:05:14,647 --> 00:05:17,275
Meanwhile, I'll ask McDougal
to give you a job.

29
00:05:17,359 --> 00:05:18,985
No way.

30
00:05:19,110 --> 00:05:21,154
It was good enough
for your old man.

31
00:05:21,237 --> 00:05:22,697
So was arthritis.

32
00:05:22,781 --> 00:05:25,784
He supported a family,
like you'll have to do.

33
00:05:25,909 --> 00:05:29,162
No. Not me.
I am not falling into that trap.

34
00:05:29,287 --> 00:05:32,123
Every man wakes up one morning
with a wife and kids.

35
00:05:32,207 --> 00:05:35,126
Where did they come from?
They weren't there before.

36
00:05:35,251 --> 00:05:40,131
That's 'cause most things in life,
good and bad, just happen to you.

37
00:05:40,215 --> 00:05:42,509
I'll make things happen for me.

38
00:05:42,592 --> 00:05:45,679
Sure you will.
That's a buck for the beer.

39
00:05:48,682 --> 00:05:52,102
What? Your nephew comes home

40
00:05:52,185 --> 00:05:55,605
from serving his country,
and doesn't even rate a free beer?

41
00:05:55,689 --> 00:05:57,982
You don't get rich
giving things away.

42
00:05:58,066 --> 00:05:59,442
How do you get rich?

43
00:05:59,526 --> 00:06:02,529
I'll give you your first lesson,
on the house.

44
00:06:02,654 --> 00:06:06,825
I've been here 25 years,
never bought a drink. Right, Eddie?

45
00:06:06,908 --> 00:06:09,119
Yeah, I can testify to that.

46
00:06:09,244 --> 00:06:13,081
In 1969,
the Mets won the World Series.

47
00:06:13,164 --> 00:06:17,293
Eddie starts pounding on the bar,
demanding a round on the house.

48
00:06:17,419 --> 00:06:21,089
"Drinks for everybody," he says.
Tell him what I did, Eddie.

49
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:25,468
He whacked me with a club. Almost
knocked the eye out of my head.

50
00:06:25,552 --> 00:06:27,095
That's how you make money?

51
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:31,599
You outwork, outthink, outscheme and
outmanoeuvre. You make no friends.

52
00:06:31,725 --> 00:06:35,478
Trust nobody. And make sure
you're the smartest guy in the room

53
00:06:35,603 --> 00:06:38,523
when the subject of money comes up.

54
00:06:38,606 --> 00:06:42,610
I don't know, Uncle Pat. It doesn't
sound like too much fun to me.

55
00:06:42,694 --> 00:06:45,947
Fun? You want fun,
you go play at the beach.

56
00:06:46,031 --> 00:06:49,034
- I think I'll try the city first.
- Well, here.

57
00:06:49,159 --> 00:06:55,415
- This will get you there in style.
- $10. Uncle Pat!

58
00:06:56,249 --> 00:06:58,126
Buy Eddie a binge on me.

59
00:06:59,336 --> 00:07:02,255
Eddie,
you got to be quicker than that.

60
00:07:28,907 --> 00:07:32,952
I've always wanted to work
on Wall Street. I read the "Journal".

61
00:07:33,078 --> 00:07:38,500
- I'll do what it takes to succeed.
- All our professionals have degrees.

62
00:07:38,583 --> 00:07:40,377
I catch on quick.

63
00:07:40,460 --> 00:07:42,504
- You're wasting your time.
- No.

64
00:07:42,587 --> 00:07:45,507
- We're not interested.
- Guy like you? Advertising.

65
00:07:45,590 --> 00:07:47,634
I have a feel for advertising.

66
00:07:47,759 --> 00:07:49,719
I can tell what's wrong with an ad.

67
00:07:49,803 --> 00:07:52,639
Mr Flanagan,
we need solid credentials.

68
00:07:52,764 --> 00:07:55,934
- A marketing degree is prerequisite.
- Try the networks.

69
00:07:56,059 --> 00:07:58,436
In the army,
I worked in communications.

70
00:07:58,520 --> 00:08:01,189
We need someone
who can hit the ground running.

71
00:08:01,272 --> 00:08:04,067
- Sorry.
- Maybe in six or eight months.

72
00:08:04,150 --> 00:08:07,153
- Pursue other avenues.
- You should re-enlist.

73
00:08:07,278 --> 00:08:10,615
I believe in positive thinking.
Never quit. Never say die.

74
00:08:10,699 --> 00:08:13,702
I want to be part of the team.
What do you think?

75
00:08:13,827 --> 00:08:16,913
Your résumé is completely inadequate.

76
00:08:17,038 --> 00:08:20,041
- I'll start at the bottom.
- You're aiming too high.

77
00:08:20,125 --> 00:08:22,669
- I'll do anything.
- You don't have experience.

78
00:08:22,752 --> 00:08:24,087
I need a job.

79
00:08:24,170 --> 00:08:26,715
- We value education.
- We require a degree.

80
00:08:26,840 --> 00:08:28,008
Go to college.

81
00:09:00,832 --> 00:09:04,753
- Bar's closed, pal.
- I'm looking for the manager.

82
00:09:04,836 --> 00:09:08,590
What's wrong?
Find a hair in your quiche?

83
00:09:10,342 --> 00:09:12,635
No. I'm looking for a job.

84
00:09:12,719 --> 00:09:15,972
I see. You want to put a hair
in somebody else's quiche.

85
00:09:16,598 --> 00:09:18,391
Just get canned?

86
00:09:18,475 --> 00:09:21,394
I'm looking for something better.

87
00:09:22,437 --> 00:09:26,358
Coughlin's Law. Anything else
is always something better.

88
00:09:27,233 --> 00:09:28,860
Coughlin's Law?

89
00:09:28,985 --> 00:09:31,905
Douglas Coughlin. Logical negativist.

90
00:09:32,030 --> 00:09:34,741
Flourished in the last part
of the 20th century,

91
00:09:34,824 --> 00:09:39,621
propounded a set of laws that
the world ignored, to its detriment.

92
00:09:39,746 --> 00:09:40,747
Me.

93
00:09:41,706 --> 00:09:45,960
- Ever work behind a bar?
- My uncle's in the business.

94
00:09:46,711 --> 00:09:48,755
You know how to make
a Red Eye, Mr...?

95
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:53,259
Brian Flanagan. No. I'm sorry.
I haven't had the pleasure as yet.

96
00:09:53,385 --> 00:09:56,304
What about a vodka martini
with a Pernod float?

97
00:09:56,888 --> 00:09:58,598
I'm a fast learner.

98
00:09:59,933 --> 00:10:03,269
Ever throw a 400lb psychopath
out of a bar?

99
00:10:03,395 --> 00:10:05,355
Guess I could if I had to.

100
00:10:05,480 --> 00:10:08,900
Or a 100lb ballerina
who's been speeding for three days?

101
00:10:09,025 --> 00:10:13,321
Just open the door and let her
pirouette out in the street?

102
00:10:13,405 --> 00:10:16,574
These are some of the tasks
you'll be asked to perform.

103
00:10:16,700 --> 00:10:20,036
This is the Upper East Side,
the saloon capital of the world.

104
00:10:20,161 --> 00:10:23,665
Are you ready for the big time,
young Mr Flanagan?

105
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:27,669
I think I can handle it.

106
00:10:31,381 --> 00:10:34,050
- Get your act together!
- Vodka and Rose's.

107
00:10:34,134 --> 00:10:37,971
Come on! I got four people waiting.
I'm not going back with three drinks.

108
00:10:38,054 --> 00:10:39,431
I know. It's coming.

109
00:10:39,514 --> 00:10:43,101
Absolut on the rocks, Gilbey's
and tonic and a Velvet Hammer.

110
00:10:43,184 --> 00:10:46,187
- I didn't order that.
- A Molson and a Cuba Libre.

111
00:10:46,312 --> 00:10:49,649
- What was that?
- A Molson and a Cuba Libre.

112
00:10:54,487 --> 00:10:57,574
If you want to sit in the water,
go to Coney Island.

113
00:10:57,699 --> 00:11:01,995
- You want me to bite the top off?
- This has got recipes.

114
00:11:02,078 --> 00:11:04,122
Orderina! Cuba Libre!

115
00:11:04,247 --> 00:11:06,916
- Can I have a glass of water?
- He can't make it.

116
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,544
- Where's my Jim Beam on the rocks?
- Coming.

117
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:13,006
I'm not leaving
till I get my Cuba Libre.

118
00:11:13,089 --> 00:11:15,550
Excuse me, could I have an Orgasm?

119
00:11:15,675 --> 00:11:18,511
This isn't what I ordered.

120
00:11:18,595 --> 00:11:22,724
You bitch! Why didn't you just
tell me it was a rum and Coke?

121
00:11:22,849 --> 00:11:24,893
Can I have what I ordered?

122
00:11:25,018 --> 00:11:26,895
- An Angel Tit.
- A white wine.

123
00:11:26,978 --> 00:11:28,855
- Pink Squirrel.
- A Friar Tuck.

124
00:11:28,980 --> 00:11:31,191
- A Dingaling.
- A white wine.

125
00:11:31,316 --> 00:11:33,193
- Pink Squirrel!
- Angel Tit!

126
00:11:33,276 --> 00:11:35,987
- Dirty Mother!
- Can I have what I ordered?

127
00:11:36,071 --> 00:11:38,114
Alright!

128
00:11:38,239 --> 00:11:41,201
- What was it that you ordered?
- A Martini.

129
00:11:41,284 --> 00:11:43,078
What's in that?

130
00:11:57,509 --> 00:12:00,929
- You get 10% from the waitresses.
- I don't deserve it.

131
00:12:01,054 --> 00:12:03,973
You schmuck,
you get money from girls every day?

132
00:12:05,225 --> 00:12:09,354
- I'm sorry I called you a bitch.
- Why? I am a bitch.

133
00:12:12,107 --> 00:12:16,277
- Got yourself a new disciple?
- Goodnight, my beautiful.

134
00:12:16,903 --> 00:12:18,446
Frogman.

135
00:12:19,155 --> 00:12:22,242
Anyone that can get money
out of her is a major talent.

136
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:25,286
Come back next Thursday.
I've got five shifts open.

137
00:12:25,412 --> 00:12:27,288
You're offering me a job?

138
00:12:29,082 --> 00:12:30,875
The waitresses hate me.

139
00:12:33,169 --> 00:12:37,799
Wait until you've given them crabs.
Then you'll really know hatred.

140
00:12:55,483 --> 00:12:58,820
Today, we'll discuss the demand
for money by focusing

141
00:12:58,945 --> 00:13:00,405
on the money multiplier.

142
00:13:00,488 --> 00:13:03,742
We add increases in currency
along the whole system,

143
00:13:03,825 --> 00:13:06,286
which gives
the sum of an infinite series.

144
00:13:06,411 --> 00:13:09,831
Adding together increases
in currency and deposits

145
00:13:09,956 --> 00:13:12,500
they add up to one plus CU
over CU plus RE.

146
00:13:12,584 --> 00:13:16,713
That, simply stated, is
the money multiplier. Now, moving on.

147
00:13:16,796 --> 00:13:19,632
The essential technique
of bartending.

148
00:13:19,716 --> 00:13:23,470
Less is more. The less you pour,
the more you score.

149
00:13:23,595 --> 00:13:25,889
The boss does better, we do better.

150
00:13:25,972 --> 00:13:27,349
And the customer?

151
00:13:27,432 --> 00:13:31,102
Think of him as a hurdler thinks
of a hurdle. A means to an end.

152
00:13:31,186 --> 00:13:35,648
We dazzle him with ice work,
we baffle him with bottle work.

153
00:13:35,774 --> 00:13:39,527
There are many ways to fool
a customer. The short pour.

154
00:13:41,029 --> 00:13:43,239
The long pour.

155
00:13:43,323 --> 00:13:47,702
The ice mountain, the spring thaw,
the speed-rack shuffle, the hot shot.

156
00:13:47,827 --> 00:13:50,288
You will learn them all.

157
00:13:50,372 --> 00:13:52,415
Yes, Obi-Wan.

158
00:13:52,540 --> 00:13:54,501
Both hands, ladies, come on.

159
00:13:54,626 --> 00:13:57,545
Ready? One, two, three, let go!

160
00:14:02,258 --> 00:14:06,096
- What does it mean?
- What does it mean? Nothing!

161
00:14:06,179 --> 00:14:08,556
Nothing? Alright!

162
00:14:15,063 --> 00:14:18,733
- Very sophisticated, man.
- What a good jolt!

163
00:14:25,031 --> 00:14:26,825
You got it going.

164
00:14:30,954 --> 00:14:33,748
Let's go with the drinks.
I'm making money tonight.

165
00:14:33,832 --> 00:14:36,042
Let's make some money for a change.

166
00:14:37,919 --> 00:14:39,379
Ice!

167
00:14:39,462 --> 00:14:41,756
- Catch!
- Thank you.

168
00:14:41,840 --> 00:14:44,759
I guess that's what you learn
in college, right?

169
00:15:00,567 --> 00:15:02,861
Don't forget my beers, Bri.

170
00:15:06,197 --> 00:15:07,991
Missed me!

171
00:15:09,659 --> 00:15:13,496
The name of the game is woman.
Little darlings come in here panting,

172
00:15:13,621 --> 00:15:18,501
their hearts pitter-patting for the
handsome, all-knowing bartender.

173
00:15:18,626 --> 00:15:23,006
In their wake, slobbering geeks
with one hand on their crotches

174
00:15:23,131 --> 00:15:25,425
and the other hand on their wallets.

175
00:15:25,508 --> 00:15:29,554
You get the women, you get the
bucks. And boy, you've got them.

176
00:15:29,679 --> 00:15:32,140
Buttons were popping,
skirts were rising.

177
00:15:32,265 --> 00:15:36,895
When you can see the colour of their
panties, you know you've got talent.

178
00:15:36,978 --> 00:15:39,814
Stick with me, son.
I'll make you a star.

179
00:15:39,898 --> 00:15:44,611
Thanks, but I gotta be honest.
This is just a part-time gig for me.

180
00:15:44,694 --> 00:15:47,781
I'm in the business programme,
City College.

181
00:15:47,906 --> 00:15:50,116
A seeker of wisdom and truth.

182
00:15:51,701 --> 00:15:55,205
You couldn't find a better
work-study programme than here.

183
00:15:55,330 --> 00:15:59,542
- To a future leader of America.
- I'll stick with the brew.

184
00:16:00,418 --> 00:16:03,338
Beer is for breakfast here.
Drink or be gone.

185
00:16:12,639 --> 00:16:14,683
I realise I've got a class

186
00:16:14,808 --> 00:16:16,851
of budding capitalists here,

187
00:16:16,935 --> 00:16:21,481
that most of you are seeking
the fast-track, lovely term,

188
00:16:21,606 --> 00:16:26,820
to a career in investment banking, or
some other socially useful pursuit.

189
00:16:26,903 --> 00:16:32,117
Nevertheless, certain antiquated
skills, such as reading and writing,

190
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:34,661
remain a part of the curriculum.

191
00:16:34,786 --> 00:16:40,208
So, for your first assignment, I want
you to write your own obituaries.

192
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:45,255
Not that I wish you were dead.
At least not yet, anyway.

193
00:16:46,339 --> 00:16:48,299
"Brian Flanagan."

194
00:16:48,425 --> 00:16:53,221
"Senator Brian Fla...
Billionaire governor Brian Flanagan

195
00:16:53,346 --> 00:16:56,766
whose self-propelled meteoric rise
to wealth and fame

196
00:16:56,850 --> 00:17:00,603
would have made
even JD Rockefeller envious,...

197
00:17:01,896 --> 00:17:04,733
..died early yesterday morning
at the age of 99,

198
00:17:04,816 --> 00:17:09,362
while bedding his 18-year-old
seventh wife, Heidi,

199
00:17:09,487 --> 00:17:12,032
who is recovering from exhaustion

200
00:17:12,157 --> 00:17:15,660
and will be unable
to attend the funeral."

201
00:17:19,622 --> 00:17:21,249
For your mid-term paper,

202
00:17:21,374 --> 00:17:25,920
I want you to select a business
in which you are interested

203
00:17:26,046 --> 00:17:29,716
and to prepare a complete plan
for its development.

204
00:17:29,799 --> 00:17:36,389
You should include capitalisation,
administrative costs,

205
00:17:36,473 --> 00:17:42,896
income prospectus, marketing,
cost analysis.

206
00:17:44,397 --> 00:17:47,901
Blue shirt, fifth row, wake up!

207
00:17:51,321 --> 00:17:54,074
Light dawns on Marble Head.

208
00:17:55,950 --> 00:17:57,410
Where was I?

209
00:18:41,454 --> 00:18:45,208
I have got serious fuck-me eyes
coming over here.

210
00:18:45,291 --> 00:18:48,795
Stay in formation. Her old man's
coming in right behind her.

211
00:19:14,154 --> 00:19:16,031
Time.

212
00:19:25,248 --> 00:19:28,043
Brian? The bottle.

213
00:19:30,253 --> 00:19:33,590
Brian? Try and make it
by closing, will you?

214
00:19:33,673 --> 00:19:36,384
I'm doing the best I can, OK?

215
00:19:41,348 --> 00:19:43,391
Sexual frustration.

216
00:19:44,476 --> 00:19:49,814
I asked you to prepare a business
plan, a seemingly simple assignment,

217
00:19:49,898 --> 00:19:54,778
and yet one word describes
your papers. Bankrupt!

218
00:19:54,903 --> 00:19:57,113
Bankrupt.

219
00:19:57,238 --> 00:20:00,325
A word some of you
will know well in the future.

220
00:20:00,450 --> 00:20:03,161
Like Mr Ron LeMaster.
Where is Ronnie LeMaster?

221
00:20:03,244 --> 00:20:07,248
Yes, our cosmetics magnate
who hopes to make his fortune

222
00:20:07,332 --> 00:20:09,793
selling make-up for pets.

223
00:20:10,877 --> 00:20:14,547
Fetch, Ronnie, fetch. Good boy.

224
00:20:14,631 --> 00:20:17,884
And my own personal favourite,
Mrs Sheila Rivkin.

225
00:20:17,967 --> 00:20:19,928
Oh, my God, he's got my paper.

226
00:20:20,053 --> 00:20:23,640
Mrs Rivkin has spent 20 years
burning her husband's dinners,

227
00:20:23,723 --> 00:20:27,769
but now wants to become the
Donald Trump of the cookie business.

228
00:20:27,852 --> 00:20:31,898
You.
You have something to contribute?

229
00:20:31,981 --> 00:20:34,442
I said it wasn't worth
getting upset about.

230
00:20:34,526 --> 00:20:36,486
What's your name?

231
00:20:36,569 --> 00:20:40,073
- Brian Flanagan.
- Speak up. Let the class hear you.

232
00:20:41,116 --> 00:20:46,329
- Brian Flanagan.
- Yes, Mr Flanagan. Let us see.

233
00:20:47,288 --> 00:20:51,835
Yes, Mr Flanagan is determined
to revolutionise the bar business,

234
00:20:51,960 --> 00:20:55,630
by franchising his version
of the local New York tavern

235
00:20:55,714 --> 00:20:58,258
to every suburban shopping mall
in America.

